# Evidence-command allowlist (ADR-009). One bare command name per line.
#
# Evidence commands re-execute later inside VERIFIER sessions (recheck),
# so everything here must be read-only: it will run with whatever the
# repository can read, in a session that did not write it. The screen
# also refuses output redirection (except to /dev/null or an fd dup
# like 2>&1), command substitution ('$()', backticks), subshells, and
# path-form programs ('./x', '/usr/bin/x') regardless of this list.
# The screen is quote-aware: a '|' inside a quoted regex is an argument.
# Pipelines of allowlisted commands pass; input redirection ('<') is
# read-only and passes.
#
# Test runners (pytest, npm test, cargo test, make) are deliberately NOT
# shipped here: a test runner executes repository code, which is exactly
# the arbitrary-execution channel being screened. Add yours below as a
# conscious, committed policy decision if you accept that trade.
#
# git is deliberately NOT shipped and MUST NOT be added for evidence use
# (ADR-021, H4). Its exec/write surface is unbounded by a flag blocklist:
# `git filter-branch --tree-filter <cmd>` is arbitrary code execution,
# and archive -o / bundle / config --file / worktree / format-patch -o /
# checkout-index / bisect run / submodule foreach / `-c <k>=!cmd` aliases
# are further exec-or-write channels. PROGRAM_ARG_DENY blunts a handful of
# top-level git flags but CANNOT make git safe -- do not rely on it. find
# and sort ARE shipped and read-only in normal use; their known write/exec
# flags (find -exec/-fprintf, sort -o/--compress-program) are refused by
# that same table, which for these bounded tools is complete as far as is
# known -- but the table is a blocklist, so prefer minimal allowlists.
grep
rg
ls
cat
head
tail
wc
find
sort
uniq
cut
tr
diff
comm
echo
printf
test
[
date
basename
dirname
realpath
stat
file
sha256sum
shasum
md5sum
jq
